The Ministry of Health on Friday announced that 158 people
have tested positive for COVID-19 from a sample size of 6,899 tested in the
last 24 hours, marking a positivity rate of 2.3 per cent. This now brings the total number of cases recorded to 321,922
out of the 3,247,589 tests conducted so far. Of the cases, 143 are Kenyans while 15 are foreigners; 88 are
males and 70 are females. "The youngest is a five-month-old child while the
oldest is 100 years,” Health Cabinet Secretary Mutahi Kagwe said in a
statement on Friday. Kitui County leads with the highest number of cases at 73,
while the others are distributed as follows: Nairobi 20, Trans Nzoia 12, Nakuru
7, Machakos 6, Mombasa 6, Nyamira 4, Nyandarua 3, Uasin Gishu 3, West Pokot 2,
Bungoma 2, Kilifi 2, Kwale 2, Laikipia 2, Nandi 2, Siaya 2, Turkana 1, Kisumu
1, Busia 1, Marsabit 1, 6 Murang’a 1, Nyeri 1, Elgeyo Marakwet 1, Garissa 1, Homa
Bay 1 and Kakamega 1. CS Kagwe further noted that 46 recoveries had been recorded
out of which 37 are from the Home-Based Isolation and Care program while 9 are
from various health facilities countrywide. Total recoveries now stand at 295,580 of which 243,021 are
from the Home-Based Care and Isolation program and 52,559 from various
facilities. No deaths were recorded today and therefore the cumulative fatalities
still stand at 5,604. The Ministry also stated that 352 patients are currently
admitted in various health facilities countrywide, while 4,028 are under the
Home-Based Isolation and Care program. “9 patients are in the Intensive Care Unit (ICU), all of
them are on ventilatory support. Another 70 patients are on supplemental
oxygen. 68 of them are in the general wards while two patients are in the High
Dependency Unit (HDU),” read the MoH statement. On the ongoing vaccination exercise, the ministry registered the
highest record of 249,772 people in the country in a day. MoH attributed the high numbers to the mass
vaccination drive that was launched on Thursday in conjunction with the
Ministry of Interior and Coordination of National Government. Meanwhile, 13,134,929 vaccines have been administered across
the country as of February 3rd 2022. Of these, 6,773,782 are partially
vaccinated while those fully vaccinated are 6,014,919 “The total number of vaccines administered in the last 24
hours is 232,166 while the total number of people fully vaccinated in the last
24 hours is 129,295,” the ministry stated. MoH also noted that 169,910 are doses administered to those
between 15 to 17 years while 176,318 are booster doses.  “The uptake of the second dose among those who received
their first dose was at 63.6%. The proportion of adults fully vaccinated was 22.1%.
The Government is working towards vaccinating a targeted population of
27,246,033,” said Kagwe.